## The Enemy Hiding in Plain Sight

Let me name the thing that's killing your AI strategy.

It's not your data infrastructure. It's not your technical talent. It's not your budget.

It's **The Borrowed Playbook**.

The Borrowed Playbook shows up in conference rooms disguised as wisdom:

*"Gartner says we should..."*

*"McKinsey recommends..."*

*"Our competitor just announced..."*

*"Best practice is to standardize AI tools across the organization for consistency and efficiency."*

Every one of those phrases should trigger alarm bells.

Not because the research is wrong. Not because the consultants are incompetent. But because the question underneath all of it is fundamentally flawed.

The Borrowed Playbook treats AI transformation as a *deployment problem*.

Something you roll out. Something you standardize. Something you measure by adoption curves and training completion rates.

But AI isn't an IT deployment.

**AI is a capability multiplier.**

And when you multiply the wrong thing, you don't get efficiency.

You get *efficient destruction* of everything that makes your organization valuable.

### What the Borrowed Playbook Gets Wrong

**When you standardize AI tools, you optimize for the lowest common denominator.**

Different teams create value differently. Your sales organization doesn't work like your engineering team. Your client advisors don't operate like your analysts. Forcing everyone onto the same tools, with the same workflows, for the sake of "consistency" means optimizing for vendor convenience instead of human differentiation.

**When you start with high-volume, repetitive tasks, you optimize for efficiency theater.**

Yes, you can prove ROI on automating data entry. You can show cost savings on document processing. But while you're celebrating those metrics, your competitors are using AI to make their experts *twice as effective* at the work that actually wins clients.

**When you build a Center of Excellence, you centralize decisions away from the people who understand the work.**

The people closest to your customers know what creates value. The people doing the actual work know where time gets wasted. A centralized AI team making decisions for the entire organization will optimize for what they can measure—which is rarely what matters most.

**When you follow the vendor implementation roadmap, you sequence activities for *their* success, not yours.**

Vendors want you to deploy their tools widely and quickly. That's how they grow revenue. Your goal is different: you need AI that amplifies what makes your organization uniquely valuable. Those objectives rarely align.

---

> **You can't borrow someone else's answer to the question: "What makes our people great?"**

