## The Numbers Don't Lie

Let me share some research that should keep you up at night.

These aren't cherry-picked statistics from vendors trying to sell you something. These are findings from MIT, McKinsey, the Federal Reserve, PwC, and peer-reviewed academic journals.

And they tell a story that contradicts almost everything you've been told about AI transformation.

### The Adoption-Value Gap

Eighty-eight percent of workers now use AI at work, compared to just twenty-two percent in 2023, according to [EY's Work Reimagined 2025 study](https://www.ey.com/en_uk/megatrends/why-shared-intelligence-will-redefine-talent).

Adoption isn't the problem. Everyone's adopting.

But here's what the MIT Media Lab found in their [State of AI in Business 2025 report](https://mlq.ai/media/quarterly_decks/v0.1_State_of_AI_in_Business_2025_Report.pdf): only five percent of AI initiatives are producing measurable profit-and-loss impact. Sixty percent of organizations evaluated AI tools, but only twenty percent reached pilot stage—and just five percent reached production.

**Read that again.**

- 88% adoption.
- 5% results.

**The gap isn't technology. The gap is intention.**

### The Failure Rate Is Accelerating

According to [S&P Global Market Intelligence's 2025 survey](https://workos.com/blog/why-most-enterprise-ai-projects-fail-patterns-that-work) of over 1,000 enterprises across North America and Europe, forty-two percent of companies abandoned most of their AI initiatives this year.

That's up from just seventeen percent in 2024.

The average organization scrapped forty-six percent of AI proof-of-concepts before they reached production.

This isn't a blip. This is a pattern accelerating in the wrong direction.

And it gets worse. [RAND Corporation's analysis](https://workos.com/blog/why-most-enterprise-ai-projects-fail-patterns-that-work) confirms that over eighty percent of AI projects fail—which is *twice* the failure rate of non-AI technology projects.

**The organizations failing fastest aren't the ones moving slowly. They're the ones following the playbook most carefully.**

### The Productivity Paradox: Winners vs. Losers

Here's where the research gets interesting.

[PwC's 2025 Global AI Jobs Barometer](https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/news-room/press-releases/2025/ai-linked-to-a-fourfold-increase-in-productivity-growth.html), which analyzed close to a billion job advertisements and thousands of company financial reports across six continents, found that productivity growth has nearly quadrupled in industries most exposed to AI.

- Seven percent growth before AI proliferation (2018-2022).
- Twenty-seven percent growth after (2018-2024).

But that growth isn't distributed evenly across all companies that adopted AI.

**It's concentrated. Heavily concentrated.**

The same PwC research shows that industries "most exposed" to AI saw three times higher growth in revenue per employee (27%) compared to those "least exposed" (9%).

A small group of organizations figured out something the others didn't. They're not deploying AI faster. They're not spending more on tools.

They're asking a fundamentally different question.

### The Amplification Premium

The market is sending a clear signal about what it values.

[PwC's Global AI Jobs Barometer](https://www.pwc.com/gx/en/news-room/press-releases/2025/ai-linked-to-a-fourfold-increase-in-productivity-growth.html) found that workers with AI collaboration skills now earn a fifty-six percent wage premium—double the twenty-five percent premium from the previous year.

That's not a reward for AI adoption. That's a reward for AI *amplification*—the ability to make human capabilities more valuable through AI collaboration.

And here's what challenges the automation narrative: job availability grew thirty-eight percent in roles *more* exposed to AI. While that's below growth in less-exposed roles, it directly contradicts the "AI replaces jobs" story.

**The organizations winning aren't cutting headcount. They're making their people more valuable.**

### The Expert Performance Paradox

Here's a finding most organizations miss entirely.

Research from [Brynjolfsson, Li, and Raymond published in The Quarterly Journal of Economics](https://academic.oup.com/qje/article/140/2/889/7990658) (May 2025) studied the introduction of generative AI across 5,172 customer-support agents.

Access to AI assistance increased worker productivity by fifteen percent on average, as measured by issues resolved per hour.

But here's the critical nuance:

> **Less experienced and lower-skilled workers improved both the speed and quality of their output.**
> 
> **The most experienced and highest-skilled workers saw small gains in speed—and small *declines* in quality.**

For your best people, generic AI deployment can actually *hurt* quality.

This is why standardization fails. This is why "deploy AI to everyone the same way" backfires. Your experts need a different approach than your novices.

The question isn't "give everyone AI."

The question is "how do we protect and amplify what experts do while accelerating how novices develop?"

### Generic Tools Fail. Amplification Succeeds.

The [MIT State of AI in Business 2025 report](https://fortune.com/2025/08/18/mit-report-95-percent-generative-ai-pilots-at-companies-failing-cfo/) identified a critical pattern:

**Generic tools like ChatGPT excel for individuals because of their flexibility, but they stall in enterprise use since they don't learn from or adapt to workflows.**

The same study found that purchasing AI tools from specialized vendors and building genuine partnerships succeeds about sixty-seven percent of the time.

Internal builds using generic tools? They succeed only one-third as often.

"Standardize AI tools across the organization" isn't just suboptimal.

**It's the *opposite* of what the evidence shows works.**

### The Change Fatigue Factor

There's a human dimension to AI failure that most strategies ignore entirely.

[Gartner research cited by NTT Data](https://www.nttdata.com/global/en/insights/focus/2024/between-70-85p-of-genai-deployment-efforts-are-failing) shows the average employee experienced ten planned enterprise changes in 2022—up from just two in 2016.

Forty-five percent of workers feel burned out by frequent organizational changes.

[Prosci's 12th Edition Best Practices in Change Management research](https://www.nttdata.com/global/en/insights/focus/2024/between-70-85p-of-genai-deployment-efforts-are-failing) found that seventy-five percent of organizations report they are either nearing, at, or past the change saturation point.

Your workforce doesn't have unlimited capacity to absorb transformation.

When you deploy AI as another top-down initiative—another standardization effort, another tool to learn, another process to change—you're spending change capacity that may not return value.

Worse: you're spending it in a way that signals to your best people that leadership doesn't understand what they actually do.

### The Talent Flight Risk

[Gallup's 2024 report](https://www.msci.org/retaining-employees-in-the-ai-powered-workplace-emerging-challenges/) found that self-reported employee turnover risk is at its highest point since 2015. Employees' long-term commitment to their organization has hit its lowest point in nine years.

Fifty-one percent of U.S. employees are open to leaving their organization.

[BCG research](https://www.bcg.com/publications/2023/how-to-attract-develop-retain-ai-talent) on digital talent found that nearly seventy-five percent of employees working in digital fields expect to leave their current role in the near future.

Career development remains the number one reason for leaving—with [nearly eighty-five percent of millennials prioritizing professional growth](https://www.phenom.com/blog/employee-retention-strategies).

**When AI is deployed to replace human judgment, talented people see no future.**

**When AI is deployed to amplify their growth, they stay and thrive.**

### The Opportunity: $15.7 Trillion

Let me end this section with the upside.

[McKinsey research](https://www.mckinsey.com/capabilities/tech-and-ai/our-insights/superagency-in-the-workplace-empowering-people-to-unlock-ais-full-potential-at-work) sizes the long-term AI opportunity at $4.4 trillion in added productivity growth potential from corporate use cases.

The [World Economic Forum](https://www.weforum.org/stories/2025/01/four-ways-to-enhance-human-ai-collaboration-in-the-workplace/) projects that AI could contribute up to $15.7 trillion to the global economy by 2030.

Primarily—and this is their word—*primarily* by amplifying human capabilities.

Not by replacing them.

**By amplifying them.**

The organizations that figure out amplification won't just survive AI transformation.

They'll capture disproportionate value from the largest economic opportunity in a generation.

