## The Amplification Difference

Let me tell you about a different company.

Same industry as the consulting firm that lost its advisors. Smaller. Fewer resources.

But they asked a different question.

Instead of *"How do we standardize AI for efficiency?"*

They asked: *"If our senior analysts excel at client relationships, how do we use AI to double their face time?"*

Different question. Completely different outcome.

### What They Did

They didn't deploy AI to replace data analysis.

They deployed AI to *eliminate* everything that kept their best people away from clients.

Report formatting. Data gathering. Meeting prep. Follow-up documentation. Administrative coordination.

All the work that filled calendars but didn't build relationships.

All the tasks that felt productive but weren't.

### The Result

**Senior analysts went from 30% client-facing time to 60%.**

Doubled.

Not by hiring more people. Not by working longer hours.

By asking one question: **"What should AI protect?"**

Client relationships needed protection. The time spent building them was being stolen by low-value work.

AI didn't touch the relationship work. AI killed the thieves.

### The Amplification Mindset

Most organizations look at AI and ask: *"What can AI do?"*

Amplification organizations ask: *"What are our best people doing that AI should never touch? And what's currently stealing time from that work?"*

The first question leads to deployment metrics.

The second question leads to capability multiplication.

